defaultThree weeks ago I visited a distressed friend, who had commissioned a ‘builder’ to carry out renovations  and install a new kitchen at her house. She was concerned about the electrical work. When I looked at it    I fo
defaultund that all the sockets in the kitchen, which were hanging down off the wall were ‘live’. They had been left in this condition for two weeks, waiting for the ‘electrician’ to return.
default She has two children in the house. The lighting circuit contained seven 
defaultjoints, at just one switch-drop, which the builder was going to just plaster into the wall. There was a taped up joint behind the washing machine, where a cable had been extended. One of the sockets had a circuit protective conductor just hanging loose, he
defaultnce there was no ‘earth’ on the socket. All the metal boxes behind the sockets had been installed without grommets to protect the cable. Live cables were hanging down from the ceiling where a wall had been partially demolished. A toilet and a sink had been
default installed in the cupboard where the fuseboard was fixed. The sink was literally two inches away from the fuseboard. 
default&#xa0;
defaultWhile I was there the builder turned up, so I challenged him about the work. It transpired that he does all his own electrical work. I men
defaulttioned the Building Regs. and the requirements of Part P and he was none the wiser. He was not an electrician, was not a competent person, had not notified Building Control, and had no idea of inspection and testing. 
defaultThis is not an unusual case, I have com
defaulte across this type of situation far too often. 
default&#xa0;
defaultDue to the dangerous state of the system, I returned the following day and made everything safe, but how many other substandard installations are going unnoticed?
default&#xa0;
defaultThe other issue here is that due to recent changes, most of this work would NOT be notifiable, he had not installed any new circuits, just wrecked the existing ones! 
