default&#xa0;
defaultSo how do we define a qualified electrician, and at what stage do we look at someone and say, yes, you are qualified, I would trust you to undertake my electrical work?
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe EAWR 1989 and BS7671:2011 both state that persons un
defaultdertaking electrical work should be competent enough to avoid danger. Neither uses the term ‘qualified’. So what do we mean by the term? Taking two definitions from different sources, the term qualified is defined as;
default&#xa0;
defaulta/. 
defaultmeeting the proper standards and r
defaultequirements and training for an office or position or task;
defaultb/. quality or skill needed for a particular activity, 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Wiring Regulations (BS7671:2011) defines a competent person as someone who;
default&#xa0;
defaultPossesses sufficient technical knowledge, relevant 
defaultpractical skills and experience for the nature of the electrical work undertaken and is able at all times to prevent danger and, where appropriate, injury to him/herself and others.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe National Occupational Standards detail the knowledge and skills requir
defaultements for persons involved in electrical  installation work, so why do we allow people who have clearly not attained these standards to carry out electrical work? 
default&#xa0;
defaultAs someone involved both in installation and in training, I have a pretty clear idea of th
defaulte standard of tradesperson I would all
defaultow to work in my house. They must know how to plan and design the installation before they start, and have taken into account the safety of myself and my family. They must possess the knowledge and understanding of ele
defaultctrical systems, to enable them to deal with any issues arising from the alteration of my installation. They must know how to inspect and test the installed installation correctly and safely
default, and be able to provide me with the proper documentation. They mu
defaultst be aware of how the installation process may affect the structure and characteristics of my home, (sound travel, fire safety, ventilation etc). They must work diligently and prevent any damage to mine or my neighbours home or the environment, and provid
defaulte me with a guarantee of their workmanship and materials. So what do I ask them for when they come to tender for the work?
default&#xa0;
defaultDo I ask to see their qualifications, and if so, which ones, and 
defaultdo qualifications on their own prove competence? 
defaultHow much experience
default do they have, or are they fresh out of college? Membership to any of the ‘approving bodies’ does not impress me either, as I have experienced many times situations where ‘members’ do not have a full understanding of what they are attempting to install.
default&#xa0;
defaultHaving studied the National Occupational Standards, I am amazed that they seem to be ‘ignored’ so blatantly by some of the ‘agencies’ that should be helping to maintain the 
defaultstandards. These NOS’s are already written, and provi
defaultde good criteria of
default what we sh
defaultould be looking for in an electrician. I would suggest that if more attention was paid to keeping to these standards, and incorporating them in any future developments in the training, assessment and qualification of electricians, the home would be a safer
default place.
default&#xa0;
defaultSo is there any existing system that sets a sensible benchmark for electrical qualifications, experience and knowledge, as well as checking health and safety awareness? Well, yes there is. Currently the J.I.B. operate a system that recognises qual
defaultifications, job experience and knowledge
default,
default and grades applicants accordingly. In conjunction with the E.C.A. they administer the E.C.S. card system.(Electrotechnical Certification Scheme). 
default&#xa0;
defaultBriefly, the ECS card is the ‘electrical equivalent’ of the CSCS ca
defaultrd 
defaultthat is 
defaultoperated on most construction sites, where possession of a card is required for all personnel to gain access to work on site.
default 
defaultThe CSCS card is awarded following successful completion of a Health &amp; safety test. The ECS card, which should be a req
defaultuirement for all persons carrying out electrical installation, requires two things;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe successful completion of a health &amp; safety exam (a different one to the CSCS card recognising   the additional hazards of electricity).
default&#xa0;
defaultApplication and award of a JIB g
defaultrade based on qualifications, experience and knowledge.
default&#xa0;
defaultOn successful achievement an applicant is provided with the ECS card which details their grading as  assessed by JIB and their details, which can then be shown to potential customers. This provides th
defaulte customer with proof of identification and 
defaultgives them a guide as to the competency of the person tendering for the work. The cost of the JIB application, grading and exam
default 
defaultis £78 in total, which is in my opinion very good value for a system which checks an
defaultd assesses your qualifications and experience, your health and safety knowledge and awareness and provides an identification card for you to show 
defaultto 
defaultcustomers. 
default&#xa0;
defaultI understand that the JIB set wage rates that are currently above some of the cheaper ‘outsi
defaultde’ labour rates, and hence 
defaultsome 
defaultfirms are looking to move away from them, in order to utilise this cheaper labour and cut costs. In the current economic climate obviously 
defaultfirms are looking at all possibilities when it comes to cutting their costs to remai
defaultn competitive. However, we must ensure that this does not also involve cutting the skills and knowledge levels of the workforce. Surely it is worth paying a little more for competent, skilled operatives, after all we would not accept imported cable just be
defaultcause it is cheaper, 
defaultunlessdefault defaultit was up to standard. The JIB/ECA 
defaultadministered 
defaultECS card scheme is the one scheme that 
defaultis currently
default capable of grading all operatives with at least some level of accuracy. 
defaultWe might not always be happy with the grade they set, BUT at least they have standards, and if someone wants to progress up through the levels they can, with training and experience. 
